            <!-- Theory / Explanation -->
            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>ACI 318 concrete shear design – key formulas</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on one-way shear design of non-prestressed
                reinforced concrete beams per ACI 318 strength design
                (φ-design). It computes the concrete contribution V<sub>c</sub>,
                the stirrup contribution V<sub>s</sub>, and the design shear
                strength φV<sub>n</sub>, then compares it to the factored shear
                V<sub>u</sub>.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Concrete shear strength V<sub>c</sub></h3>
              <p>
                For a typical non-prestressed beam with minimum web
                reinforcement, a common simplified expression for the nominal
                concrete shear strength is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>US units (kips, in, ksi)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  V<sub>c</sub> = 2 λ √f'<sub>c</sub> · b<sub>w</sub> · d / 1000
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  f'<sub>c</sub> in ksi, b<sub>w</sub> and d in inches → V<sub
                    >c</sub
                  >
                  in kips
                </p>
                <hr class="my-2" />
                <p><strong>SI units (kN, mm, MPa)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  V<sub>c</sub> = 0.17 λ √f'<sub>c</sub> · b<sub>w</sub> · d /
                  1000
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  f'<sub>c</sub> in MPa, b<sub>w</sub> and d in mm → V<sub
                    >c</sub
                  >
                  in kN
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Here λ is the lightweight concrete modification factor (λ = 1.0
                for normalweight concrete).
              </p>

              <h3>2. Shear reinforcement strength V<sub>s</sub></h3>
              <p>For vertical stirrups crossing the shear crack:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>V<sub>s</sub> = A<sub>v</sub> f<sub>y</sub> d / s</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  A<sub>v</sub> = total area of stirrup legs crossing the shear
                  plane per spacing s. Use consistent units (US: in², in, ksi →
                  kips; SI: mm², mm, MPa → N → kN).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Nominal and design shear strength</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>V<sub>n</sub> = V<sub>c</sub> + V<sub>s</sub></p>
                <p>φV<sub>n</sub> = φ (V<sub>c</sub> + V<sub>s</sub>)</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  Typical φ for shear in ACI 318 is 0.75 (check the edition and
                  member type).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Design check</h3>
              <p>The strength requirement is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>V<sub>u</sub> ≤ φV<sub>n</sub></p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator reports the utilization ratio V<sub>u</sub> /
                φV<sub>n</sub>. Values ≤ 1.0 indicate adequate shear strength;
                values &gt; 1.0 indicate that the section is under-designed in
                shear.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Practical tips for using this calculator</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Always use <strong>factored shear V<sub>u</sub></strong> from
                  your load combinations (e.g. 1.2D + 1.6L).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Ensure b<sub>w</sub> and d correspond to the same section
                  where V<sub>u</sub> is evaluated (typically at d from the face
                  of support).
                </li>
                <li>
                  When entering A<sub>v</sub>, include all legs of the stirrup
                  crossing the shear plane (e.g. 2 legs for a typical closed
                  stirrup).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check ACI 318 for additional limits on maximum stirrup spacing
                  and maximum usable V<sub>s</sub>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                This calculator is for educational and preliminary design use
                only. Always verify results and comply with the latest ACI 318
                provisions and your local design codes.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Does this calculator design the required stirrup spacing?</h3>
              <p>
                It currently evaluates a given section: you enter the stirrup
                area A<sub>v</sub> and spacing s, and it reports V<sub>s</sub>,
                V<sub>n</sub>, and φV<sub>n</sub>. A common workflow is to start
                with a trial spacing, check the utilization, and then adjust s
                until V<sub>u</sub> ≤ φV<sub>n</sub>.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use it for T-beams or flanged sections?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, provided that you use the correct web width b<sub>w</sub>
                and effective depth d for the web. The shear design in ACI 318
                is based on the web dimensions; the flange mainly affects
                flexural capacity, not one-way shear.
              </p>

              <h3>What about deep beams or shear walls?</h3>
              <p>
                Deep beams, transfer girders, and shear walls often require
                special provisions (strut-and-tie models, sectional
                shear-friction, etc.) that are beyond the scope of this
                simplified tool. For such members, use the appropriate ACI 318
                chapters and more advanced design methods.
              </p>
            </section>
